‚óŹ This shifts the picture. Three things to flag:

  1. The bisect was invalid. lsmod shows mt7925e loaded with all 4 dependents.
  The dmesg even logged Module mt7925e is blacklisted at t+21s ‚ÄĒ the kernel
  rejected one load attempt ‚ÄĒ but something loaded it later anyway.
  module_blacklist= on the kernel cmdline isn't bulletproof; we need
  boot.blacklistedKernelModules (which writes a modprobe.d file that
  udev/modprobe respect) plus modprobe.blacklist= on the cmdline as
  belt-and-suspenders.

  2. New cache, same shape. This crash hit anon_vma_chain (a VMA struct), not
  skbuff_small_head. Detected by wpctl calling mprotect() ‚Üí __split_vma ‚Üí
  anon_vma_clone. But the corruption signature is identical to round 2: exactly
  16 bytes (two pointer-shaped values) written into the body of a freed object,
  redzones intact, padding intact. That's not random hardware noise ‚ÄĒ that's a
  structured write through a stale pointer. The cache differs because the freed
  memory got recycled to different consumers.

  3. Two pointer-shaped writes into freed objects = classic use-after-free where
   someone holds a stale list-head pointer and does a list update on it after
  free. Cache identity is downstream of timing.

  So the producer hypothesis is intact ‚ÄĒ but it's now writing through a pointer
  to "memory that recently held something", not specifically an SKB. Could still
   be mt7925e (we don't actually know ‚ÄĒ bisect was invalid). Could be amdxdna,
  amdgpu, etc. Or firmware/microcode.

  Plan: redo the mt7925e bisect properly, and in parallel push BIOS to LVFS top
  of queue.

  Let me check the config and update it.

